ccomplished.\nJn !s the product of oao man s\nThat man. Viceroy Yuan Shi\nnrw nrlme mlalstAr\nhat in Peking for the purpose\nxicg oat his sam plans for\n3t.ie empire as he has doae for\na city. Therefore -what Tientsin\n!av China will be, and III be\nsn. for I believe Mr. Hobert\nvws -what he Is talklrg about\nr fc ays that the conviction that\na mast have progress and the\n\"inatioa to change has seized\nevpry official of high standing\non ead of the oaapire to the\nAnd I believe that every one\nK\" 's the Chinese agrees that\nChinaman has the will\nJ Had the way.\nChina Is progressing by leaps\nIliads is true, bat that the\ntarse of carelessness and sucer\nThe Chinese government Is surely\ndoing its best. Gambling: has been\nproulbited within the dtr on itoln'nf\ntea years\" Imprisonment gambltag; In\nevery form. A search for an rxilum\nden proved the efficiency of the law.\nana inspection wiped them out of ex\nistence.\nPerhnps the least said about the out\nraseous doings of the foreigners In\nTientnln the better. It Is a subject\nthat people do not like to discuss and\ndo not wish to have brought before\nthem. It is true, nevertheless, that\nIn the foreign settlements the Chlnose\nare finding endless opportunity for\nthe gambling which is nrohlbited bv\ntheir government In their own city.\nand Is nevertheless openly coun\ntenanced by several consuls of for\neign nations In spite of their agree\nments with the Chinese Government\n-The China Times,\" a Tientsin paper,\nis waging an open war ncnlust houses\nof III fame and places of amusement\nof outrageous character which are act\nually protected by the representatives\nof foreign powers. The papers are\nfull of It. One paragraph 1 will copy,\nfor It Is suggestive and can stand by\nItself: \"The Alhnmbrn Its Pic\ntures: Mr. Pratt. Ilritlsh vice con\nsul, sat In tho Ilritlsh consular\ncourt on Saturday morning to hear\na charge against Mr. A. Harper of\nthe Alhambra Russian concession of\nexposing Indocont plctutes. Tho\nconsul for defonse: Th first one\nhe thought was undoubtedly coarse,\nas to tho second and third that\nvere called Indecent, that, of\ncourse, was a matter not of indi\nvidual opinion so much as of opin\nion or tho court trying tho case. It\nwas rather a stretch of the Imag\nination to say that one of tho\nreasons for objecting was that tho\nChinese went there, and that it did\nnot look woll for Chinese to see\nxrhnf fnrilcrnnt-a ll.l (rxLtlila It..\nhad no doubt foreigners did lots\nof things the Chinese did not ap\nprove of. If these pictures were\npermitted In London he did not sef\nwhy they should not bo pormltted\nhero.\" People have n way of saving\nthat \"There nln't no Ten Command-\nmeats beyond Suo. and then dismiss\ning the matter with tho feeling that\nthey have made a rather clever and\ntelling observation.\nDo they realize. I wonder, that In\nsome Chinese ports the term American\nwoman Is synonymous for woman of\nill repute or prostitute? Thank God\nIt is not so in Tientsin. Tho American\nand British governments aro nctlng so\nfar as Christian nations In this city,\neven If tho Individual American men\nand Hritishers are showing themsolves\nanything but Christians. Tho Chi\nnese government Is not going to\n\"stand for this\" long. There wMl bo\na day of reckoning if the foreign con\ncessions go on nutting a premium on\nvice as they are doing now. Men\nwho have lived In Tientsin for years\ndo not hesitate to say that matters\nmust como to n crisis soon. It Is\nIn the Interest of the neoulo at homo\nand of the United States, It seems to\nmo, to understand what is going on.\nThis brings me to my third nolnt.\nwhich includes a kind of Biimniarv of\nall the rest, namely, the Important po\nsition of tho Y. M. C. A. In Tientsin.\nA record of some of the activities of\nmy very good friend Mr. Robertson\nwill bo most conclusive In showing\nthat the Y. M. C. A. Is a power for edu\ncation and for righteousness needed\nand esteemed by tho Chinese educa\ntors. On one side Mr. Robertson\ncomes In contact with a vast number\nof school boys. Ho has several\nclasses In various schools In physics,\nand tnko3 his studonts to nil the cen\nters of the city, such us the Western\ntelegraph station, tolephone building,\npower plant, etc. He also la manag\ning a regular athletic campaign, has\nIntroduced tho games of association\nfootbnll. coaches tho teaniH nnd pro\nmotes the truly western Idea of \"be\ning a thorough sport.\"\nThrough the efforts and nersonnlltv\nof Mr. Galley and Mi. Robertson the\nY. M. C. A. is In a nosltlon whore It\ncan have a tremendous Influence for\nsound education and rlghteoUHtiosH if\nthe wheels can only bo ollod with a\nlittle uioro money.\nTwo elomonts are at work trylnc to\nrreaio prosperity, and both seem tn\nemanate from the same source. Cor\ntain Wall street Interests havo been\nforcing up tho price of securities for\nsome weeks until railroad and Indus\ntrial stocks are higher than bofore tho\npanic occurred. Then wo havo tho\nNational Prosperity association iralnir\nup so far as to sot Juno 1 for tho birth\nof tho now prosperity that Is to en\nvelop us with a golden mantle. Tho\nplan seoms to bo to boost stocks In\nWall street so that tho railroads can\nborrow more monoy, which from tho\nHarrlman-Rockofoller point of view\nI.h a uro sign of prosporlty.\nTho manufacturers aro to do their\npart by starting up all tho factories\non full time and, of course, selling tho\nprouuets at full prices.\nWhether this hotbed nrocosn of nrn.\nduclng prosperity will work can, of\ncourse, be only surmised, but as tho\nprimary heat furnished bv the stock\nmarket manipulators does not seem\nto nave wanned up tho lambs to tho\nnecessary onthuslasm. nrlces are or.\nratlc and Inclined to sag. The lambs\nnave been shorn too lately and closely\nto oe expected to show much ontlm!\nasm until their fleeces have had tlmo\nto grow enough to cover their naked-\nness.\nThere Is no doubt that all tho tariff.\npp- -;cted trusts can start nrnrinntinn\non a targe scale, but whether the con\nsumers can pay the high prices necos\nsary ror this hotbed brand of pros\nperlty is more than doubtful. To ovnr\nstock tho market with manufactured\ngoods that many neonlo in tholr nnv\nerty through lack of emnlovinont can\nnot pay for. will hardly help matters\nuiuess me trusts are prepared to ro-\nauce prices ana thus stimulate demaud.\nAs the Republican congress has re\nrused to reform the tariff, tho tariff\nprotected trusts still havo the power\nto collect their share of thn tariff tnx-\nand Judging from tho action of tho\nsteel trust, the boof trust, tho sugar\ntrust and many others, In detcrmln\nlng not to reduce prices, thoy evident\nJy do not Intend to divide their pros\nperlty with their customers.\nThe people generally must have\nmonoy in tneir pockets before Drosnor\nlty returns. Confidence Is a child of\nslow growth, nnd until confidence is\nrestored it Is much to bo feared that\nprosperity, nourished by the cornora\nHons for tholr own selfish ends, will\nnardly be deep enough to reach the\nnomes of tho people.\nWho has confidence in anv nros\nperlty for the people from Wall street\nmanipulators?\nWho expects prosperity to bo pro-\naucea by the railroads advancing\nrates?\nCan prosperity como to the people\nby paying the trusts more than fhov\ncnargo foreigners?\nWho can have any sonfldence that\nuepubllran policies will nroduce nro\nperlty since the panic, and with tho\nbusiness of the country still at low\nebb.'\nA presidential year Is not a boom\nI 5ear, and good crops will have to bo\nassured and marketed before tho bus\nlng power of the peonlo acaln assures\nprosperity. Tho boast of tho Repub\nlican politicians that tho tariff that\nprotects the trusts assures prosperity\nhas been rudely shattered during tho\npast year, and their do nothlnc nollcv\nduring the session of congress has not\ncondoned their evident deslro to servo\nthe trusts and corporations moro than\ntne people.\nEveryone wantB nrosnerltv. certain\nly for himself, and may bo depended\nupon to do what ho can to secure 1L\nif tho people can secure a fair deal\nthey will be prosperous, but with tho\nRepublican nollcv of nrotectlnir the\ntrusts and corporations In nlundorlne\nthem by high prices and still higher\nrates for transportation, tho brand\nof prosperity that has been and Is to\nbe handed out. Is of tho Doad-soa-ap-\nple vnrlety that crumbles nt tho touch\nof Investigation. Pleaso keop cqpl\nana give ino people a cnanco to ro\ncuporate. Under bad laws, and tho\nstand-pat policy that our Republican\ngovernors have forced us to boar, the\ngrowth of hotter times will bo slow,\nfor the people, though tho trusts and\ncorporations should soon flourish as\ntho green bay trco.\nParis Pattern No. 2419. All Seams\nAllowed. This pretty thouch extreme-\nly simple llttlo model. Is particularly\nadaptable to waists of thin silk, or\norgandie. The body lining may bo of\nthe samo material or of lawn, and tho\nfullness Is shirred into the neck and\nheld in placo by tho hieb collnr of\nall-over lace. Tho sleeves which aro\ncut In ono with tho waist are gath\nered Into cuffs of tho all-over laco and\nmay be made In full or three-quartor\nlength, according to taste. Tho hlch\ndraped girdle Is made of material sim\nilar to the waist. The pattern Is In\nthroo sizes 13 to 17 years. For a\nmiss of 15 years tho waist renuires\n3V4 yards of material 20 Inches wide.\n2 yards 27 Inches wido, two yards\ndo inches wide, or 1 yard 42 inches\nwide; as illustrated. yard of all-\nover lace 18 Inches wide.\nTn nrnnir tViU nnttam an a in\nto \"Pntfrn Ilfinnrtrnnnf nf nnnn\n1 viia .j u ,jv\nWrite rnimn n nil mliln nlnlnlv nn.i i.A\nBure to give lzu and number of pattern.\nNO. 2419. si2b,\nNAME\nTOWN\nSTRKET AND NO\nSTATE\nCHILD'S DRESS.\nPnrls Pattern No. 1482. All Seama\nAllowed. This llttlo slip dross with\ndeep square yoke Is ono of tho pretty\nmodels always popular for children.\nMade in Perslnn lawn, tho yo